Though I agree with many of Mr. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kageyama</ENAMEX> 's comments , I believe he points the gun in the wrong direction : It is n't the <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Americans</ENAMEX> who must be criticized for not understanding the <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Japanese</ENAMEX> culture , but the <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Japanese</ENAMEX> who insist on forcing their culture on <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Americans</ENAMEX> .
The <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Japanese</ENAMEX> want us to accept their culture , but they refuse to accept the <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">American</ENAMEX> culture .
<ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Japanese</ENAMEX> managers ca n't expect <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Americans</ENAMEX> to behave as if they were <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Japanese</ENAMEX> ; instead , they must manage <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Americans</ENAMEX> as <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Americans</ENAMEX> .
<ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Americans</ENAMEX> are expected to conform to the <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Japanese</ENAMEX> culture when in <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Japan</ENAMEX> .
